Basically mages DO lack a big offensive AA skill, like Manaburn or Lifeburn.<br>
<br>
We have Turn summoned...which is only Good in the Hole...MGB..em so we want to buff everyone for Talendor with +33 FR? *boggle*...Frenzied Burnout is...pathetic?<br>
People point to the power of Dire charmed pets...<br>
<br>
Folk have tossed this one around for a while, why not seriously <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> STATE</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> what we would like as a class defining <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;OMFG!! look at THAT!!!!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> power? Something that is impressive and lethal?<br>
<br>
I suggest making FRENZIED BURNOUT summon a totally helacious pet, triple sized, lvl 60, immune to fire, cold, poison and disease, 255 MR, immune to charms. Hits for 125 hp, quads, flurries, SOWed, 10k hp. Costs a black sapphire and drains all mana (thus keeping it inline with Manaburn, our use of reagents and making it rare and expensive to cast, must be FM to cast). Duration is 10 minutes.<br>
Refresh time 8 real life hours (using it should be uber rare and special)<br>
<br>
The using all mana up, makes a point about mages being something OTHER than summoning rods. On raids folk would WANT that pet up on hard long fights, like Tunare, THO etc.<br>
<br>
Sure it's more powerful than the epic, so what? You AIN'T gonna cast it very much, are you? Just like Manaburn. Would be kept for emergencies and raids.<br>
<br>
Opinions and thoughts? Would YOU like to see this as the mage's class defining skill? If so, what would you change, realziing that it MUST be a skill rarely used and costly to keep balance.<br>
If not, what would you say should be the mage class defining AA skill?<br>
